My Dad has been with me since Thursday - he's visiting because he's ill ... at this moment I am his sole caretaker. We returned to the physician's office today for the 2nd time in just a few days. A nice lady came in to get his vitals. For the Grace of God I'll never know why I asked this question ... in hindsight I believe a higher being was watching over. Out of nowhere I asked her, " Do you have any kiddos?" She stopped typing midstream, gazed over and responded, "I used to, he died in June from leukemia." I kept eye contact, I held silence for a few moments before I said, "I am deeply sorry!" She was tearful and I believe a part of her wanted to "save me, her and/or us." She quickly an enthusiastically asked, "How was your Mother's Day?" I replied it was tolerable this year, I didn't even cry. I have yearned for a child and family but it has not happened." She returned the words I am sorry. We had a moment where we met each other deeply and profoundly. I am reminded of the quote: "...people can only meet you as deeply as they've met themselves." -Matt Kahn | Grief and loss are real and we need to stay in that space, hold silence and realize it is within that silent vessel that the experience of being seen and (at least partially) understood can reveal itself.
